\begin_layout Itemize
The prototypical open set is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

-neighborhood you've already encountered:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset


\series bold
-neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset


\series default
 is the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{\epsilon}(a)=\{x\in\mathbb{R}:|x-a|<\epsilon\}=(a-\epsilon,a+\epsilon).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $O\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
open 
\series default
if for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in O$
\end_inset

, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

-neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}(a)$
\end_inset

 that's also contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Consider the open interval
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(c,d)=\{x\in\mathbb{R}:c<x<d\}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in(c,d)$
\end_inset

 be arbitrary.
 [draw] If we take 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=\min\{x-c,d-x\}$
\end_inset

 [the distance to the closest endpoints; draw], then it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}(x)=(x-\epsilon,x+\epsilon)$
\end_inset

 is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $(c,d)$
\end_inset

.
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $x-\epsilon\geq x-(x-c)=c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\epsilon\leq x+(d-x)=d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

