\begin_layout Itemize
The union of open intervals is also open.
 This observation leads to the next result:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(i) The union of an arbitrary (potentially uncountable) collection of open
 sets is open.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(ii) The intersection of a finite collection of open sets is open.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(i) How do we label the elements of a potentially-uncountable set 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

? Well, no matter how many elements there are, we can put the elements of
 the set into one-to-one correspondence with 
\emph on
some 
\emph default
(perhaps uncountable) set, call it 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 This effectively 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

labels
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 each element of 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 with a corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

, so we can call each element of 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\{O_{\lambda}:\lambda\in\Lambda\}$
\end_inset

 to represent our collection of open sets, no matter how many there are.
 This is standard notation; mathematicians often index uncountable sets
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{\lambda}\}_{\lambda\in\Lambda}$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

's are the elements of our uncountable set and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

's are labelings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now, let 
\begin_inset Formula $O=\bigcup_{\lambda\in\Lambda}O_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in O$
\end_inset

.
 We want to show that there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $(a-\epsilon,a+\epsilon)\subseteq O$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in O$
\end_inset

, we must have that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in O_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Because we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 to be open, there exists a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}(a)\subseteq O_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 But since 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{\lambda}\subseteq O$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}(a)\subseteq O$
\end_inset

 as well, completing the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(ii) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{O_{1},O_{2},\dots,O_{N}\}$
\end_inset

 be a finite collection of open sets.
 Now, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\bigcap_{k=1}^{N}O_{k}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is an element of each of the open sets.
 By the definition of an open set, we know that, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq k\leq N$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon_{k}}(a)\subseteq O_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We are in search of a 
\emph on
single 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

-neighborhood that is contained in every 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{k}$
\end_inset

, so the trick is to take the smallest one.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon=\min\{\epsilon_{1},\epsilon_{2},\dots,\epsilon_{N}\}.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that 
