\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

-neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 looks like 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\epsilon,\epsilon)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\in V_{\epsilon}(0)\cap(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We claimed earlier that closed-ness had something to do with limits of sequences
; let's try and put that link together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a limit point of a set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\lim a_{n}$
\end_inset

 for some sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n})$
\end_inset

 contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\neq x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise

\series bold
(reading question) 
\series default
Prove the backwards direction; that is, prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\lim a_{n}$
\end_inset

