\begin_inset Formula $(\impliedby)$
\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim a_{n}=x$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\in A$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\neq x$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\epsilon}(x)$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

-neighborhood.
 The (topological) definition of convergence assures us that there is a
 term 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{N}$
\end_inset

 in the sequence satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{N}\in V_{\epsilon}(x)$
\end_inset

, and the proof is complete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $(\implies)$
\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a limit point of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 In order to produce a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n})$
\end_inset

 converging to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we'll consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

-neighborhoods obtained using 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=1/n$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a limit point of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, every neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1/n}(x)$
\end_inset

 intersects 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in some point other than 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, we can choose a point
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}\in V_{1/n}(x)\cap A
\]

\end_inset

with the stipulation that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\neq x$
\end_inset

.
